each us in our current moment of environmental crisis. Until the trauma of the Civil War, many Americans sought to shape society into what they thought of as an Arcadia-not an Eden where fruit simply fell off the tree, but a public garden that depended on an ethic of communal care, and whose sense of beauty and repose related directly to an acknowledgement of mortality and limitation. Sachs explores the notion of Arcadia in the works of nineteenth-century nature writers, novelists, painters, horticulturists, landscape architects, and city planners, and holds up for comparison the twenty-first century's-and his own-tendency toward denial of both death and environmental limits. His far-reaching insights suggest new possibilities for the environmental movement today and new ways of understanding American history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aArcadia in art. 0aArcadia in literature. 0aCemeterieszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aEnvironmental responsibilityzUnited States. 0aEnvironmentalismxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aHuman ecologyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030017640740uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030018905640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300189056423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300189056/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY